observations.recommendation:
We reiterated our recommendation that Management:

Create an Inventory Committee that would facilitate conduct of physical count of the Agency’s assets pursuant to Section 124, Volume I of the Manual on NGAS for LGUs. The RPCPPE must be submitted not later than January 31 of each year to the Office of the Auditor, and the same must be reconciled with the records of the Accountant; 


Require the Municipal Treasurer and Accountant to properly maintain Stock Cards, Property Cards, SLC and PPELC and conduct periodic reconciliation of property and accounting records to come up with accurate reports;


Require the Property Officer/Municipal Treasurer to prepare AREs upon issuance of property and equipment and to look into the records of all properties of the Agency and issue AREs thereof to the concerned officials and employees in possession of or are using the same. Moreover, ensure that AREs are renewed every three years pursuant to the existing regulations to safeguard government property from possible loss or misappropriation; and


Avail the one-time cleansing of PPE account balances, strictly in accordance with COA Circular No. 2020-006, particularly on the disposition and derecognition of non-existing/missing PPE and adjust the books accordingly, in order to come up with a reliable PPE balances that are verifiable as to existence, condition and accountability.

We reiterated our recommendation that Management:

Direct Officers and Employees with CAs to immediately submit their liquidation papers or refund the amount advanced, otherwise, require the immediate withholding of salary of those officers and employees who were unable to comply with the requirement; 


Require the Municipal Accountant to closely monitor the liquidation of outstanding CAs and regularly send written demand on the submission of liquidation report or refund thereof. Moreover, look into the details of the Due from Officers and Employees account and reclassify to the Advances to Officers and Employees account amounts pertaining to advances for travel and ensure that proper accounts are used in recording the transactions pertaining to CAs; 

Stop the practice of granting additional CAs to those who have unliquidated CAs unless the previous ones are fully settled; and 

Institute the appropriate legal actions/sanctions against those erring AOs/employees and be reminded that the Auditor may order the suspension of their salaries, as cited in Section 9.2 and 9.3 of COA Circular No. 2012-004.

We recommended that Management:

Follow the Perpetual Inventory System in recording the payment for supplies and materials purchased by debiting the appropriate inventory account; 


Require the Municipal Treasurer to prepare the SSMI to consolidate the supplies and materials issued from the RIS and submit the same to the Municipal Accountant;


Stop the practice of recording the purchase of supplies and materials as outright expense. The Municipal Accountant must ensure that proper accounting entries are made, supported by the SSMI and the original copy of the RIS, to record issuance of supplies and materials;

Require the Municipal Treasurer and Municipal Accountant to maintain stock cards and SLCs, respectively, for all items of inventory. Periodic reconciliation of records must be undertaken to avoid misstatements in the quantity and amount of inventories; and 


Create an Inventory Committee and conduct physical count of inventories semi-annually and prepare and submit the RPCI to the Auditor within the period prescribed.

We recommended that Management be more prudent in the utilization of its LDRRMF, taking into consideration the existing rules and regulations governing the utilization of the said fund and require the:

MDRRMO and Municipal Budget Officer to allocate funds for the repair, maintenance and improvement of DRRM assets chargeable against MOOE of the MDRRM Office or the Mayor’s Office, in the General Fund;


Concerned officials to ensure that the release and use of the LDRRMF are supported with the required documents such as Sanggunian Resolution and declaration of state of calamity;


Concerned officials and employees to refund the cash advanced for travel purposes charged against the Special Trust Fund;


MDRRMC, through the MDRRMO, to incorporate in the LDRRMFIP and utilize the LDRRMF for tangible projects and activities that will help build disaster resilient communities and enhance disaster preparedness and response capabilities of the Municipality; 

MSWDO to submit to the Auditor all relief distributions sheets as soon as possible for verification of this Office; and

Municipal Accountant to ensure that relief distribution sheets and other proof of distribution are attached to the DVs covering the purchase of relief goods for distribution.

We recommended that:

Management require the AOs in the MTO to strictly comply with the timely remittance/deposit of their collections as provided in Section 32 Volume I of the Manual of the NGAS for LGUs;

The AOs exercise diligence in the preparation of RCD and recording of transactions in the cashbook to avoid complexity and discrepancies with other records;

The Municipal Treasurer remind the Collecting clerks to stop the practice of partial remittance. Instead, the collections must be remitted with their corresponding RCDs and their details of collection simultaneously in order to facilitate the proper segregation of collections to their respective funds; and

The Municipal Accountant prepare subsidiary ledgers per AO to show the details of collections and remittances as support for the Cash-Local Treasury account.

We recommended that the LCE:
Direct officers and employees with cash advances to immediately submit their liquidation papers, otherwise, require the immediate withholding of salary of those officers and employees who were unable to comply with the requirement;
Require the Municipal Accountant to closely monitor the liquidation of outstanding cash advances and serve again written demand on the submission of liquidation reports within the reglementary period and maintain SLs;
Stop the practice of granting additional cash advances to those who have unliquidated cash advances; and
Fast track the recovery of the documents relevant to the long outstanding cash advances and conduct verification, analysis and validation of them to determine their settlement/collectability and pursue collection, refund or liquidation, if warranted.

We recommended that the LCE:
Direct the Municipal Treasurer, the Liquidating Officers and the Collectors to deposit/turnover all future collections intact and not to retain portion of them pursuant to the aforecited provisions;
Direct the Municipal Treasurer and the Municipal Accountant to reconcile the difference between their records of the Cash – Local Treasury account balance, submit their working papers/reconciliation documents to the Office of the Auditor, and prepare necessary correcting entries in the Agency’s books or cashbooks;
Require the Municipal Accountant to prepare and maintain SLs per collecting officer and ensure regular reconciliation of the same with the records of the Municipal Treasurer;
Review previous years’ reports, schedules and other documents to determine on which of the former Municipal Treasurers had the undeposited collections amounting to ₱1,892,784.28; and
Strengthen internal control over collections, remittances and deposits to avoid retention of big amounts of money in the hands of the accountable officers and consider the promulgation and implementation of a policy on the following:
Verification by the Municipal Treasurer of the unused accountable forms in the possession of collecting clerks upon remittance to ensure that all collections are remitted daily and intact; and
Limitations in the issuance of receipts to the collectors, including the non-issuance of new stubs of receipts to those with unremitted collections.

We reiterated our recommendation that Management:
Refrain from purchasing supplies and materials on several instances through the year, instead, plan the procurement of all offices meticulously and judiciously and purchase the supplies by bulk on a quarterly basis through the BAC to avoid procurement per office as the need arises;
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to properly account for the acquisition and issuance of the supplies and materials inventory by adopting the Perpetual Inventory System and make the necessary adjustments to reflect the correct balance of the affected inventory and expense accounts;
Require all the Inventory Custodians to ensure that all issuances of supplies and materials are covered by RIS and the Municipal Treasurer to use the RIS as basis for the preparation of the SSMI. Also, instruct the Municipal Treasurer to submit the SSMI to the Municipal Accountant together with the original copies of the RIS which will be the basis of the latter to record in the books the expended portions of supplies and materials;
Direct the Municipal Treasurer to conduct periodic physical count of all supplies and materials on hand, submit the required RPCI and coordinate with the Municipal Accountant to reconcile the same with the accounting records; and
Require the Municipal Treasurer and the Municipal Accountant to properly maintain, update and reconcile the SCs and SLCs, respectively.

We recommended that Management:
Create an Inventory Committee to conduct an inventory of the local roads and prepare and submit the RPCLRN;
Require the Municipal Engineer to provide the Inventory Committee with complete description and cost segregation of road components for road projects to facilitate the preparation of RPCLRN;
Direct the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer to prepare and maintain separate SLs/LRNLCs and LRNPCs, respectively, for local road projects and reconcile both records to ensure proper recording and control of the assets;
Require the Municipal Treasurer to prepare and submit the RLRN and Local Road Inventory and Road Map; and
Require the Municipal Accountant to prepare a lapsing schedule for the computation of the depreciation for each component of road network and provide proper and complete disclosure of the total road networks in the Notes to FS in accordance with the provisions of COA Circular No. 2015-008.

We recommended that the LCE:
Require the Municipal Accountant to submit immediately the trial balances from January to November 2023 and the quarterly FS for the 2nd and 3rd quarters of CY 2023 together with all the supporting financial/accounting reports, to facilitate the review and analysis of the accounts appearing in the financial reports and to affirm the reliability of Management’s assertions;
Consider hiring additional competent staffs and personnel in the Accounting Office to hasten the process of preparation and submission of monthly, quarterly and annual financial reports to the Office of the Auditor;
Direct the Municipal Accountant-Designate, the Municipal Treasurer and the Municipal Budget Officer to be mindful of the deadlines and adhere with the provisions of Sections 70 and 73 of NGAS Manual, specifically on the submission of trial balances, FS, SAAOB and other supporting schedules; and
Evaluate the process of preparing the reports and relevant documents in the Accounting, Treasury and Budget Offices and come up with procedures/methods to cope up with the submission of financial reports to COA. Constantly remind the Municipal Treasurer and other concerned Offices within the LGU to submit the pending reports/documents to the Municipal Accountant in order to avoid delay in the preparation and submission of financial reports to COA.

We recommended that Management:
Direct the LSB to refrain from expending beyond the appropriated budget per PPA and the MBO observe diligence in posting in RAAO to properly monitor the correct balances and to avoid overspending. Likewise, direct the MBO to coordinate with the LSB regarding the Approved Annual Budget for SEF of the Municipality to ensure that correct appropriations per PPA are reflected in RAAO. Also, reconciliation between SEF Utilization Report and RAAO be undertaken to avoid discrepancies;
Submit an explanation and additional documents, if warranted, to justify the incurrence of a budget deficit;
Require the Municipal Accountant to ensure that proper accounts are used in the recording of the financial transactions and supporting documents thereof are complete. Further, make necessary adjusting entries to rectify the overstated Accounts Payable account; and
Direct the LSB to ensure that prescribed planning and budgeting tools are effectively utilized and the timelines in the planning and budgeting process are strictly observed as prescribed under DepEd-DBM-DILG JC No. 1, s. 2017.

We recommended that the LCE:
Ensure preparation of the complete LDRRMFIP including the PPAs to be charged against the STF-DRRMF and ensure efficient utilization of the same;
Direct the LDRRM Officer to assess the adequacy and availability of basic rescue and response equipment in the LDRRM Office and to prioritize, in his preparation of the LDRRMFIP for CY 2024, the procurement of early warning systems, search rescue and retrieval equipment and other equipage that are useful for the disaster preparedness and response;
Require the personnel who attended the capacity building for CLUP activity to submit to the Municipal Accountant the ORs for the registration fee, the certificates of appearance/training, tickets/receipts/certifications for the transportation expenses, which must also be submitted by the Municipal Accountant to the Office of the Auditor as soon as possible; and
Direct the Municipal Accountant, the Municipal Budget Officer and the Municipal Treasurer to initiate the transfer of CYs 2016 and 2017 unutilized fund of the STF back to GF which shall be made available for other social services.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor, through the MSWMB:
Include in the Municipal’s AIP the PPAs listed in the 10-year SWM Plan and prepare and submit to the Audit Team the accomplishment thereof as of year-end;
Strictly enforce and intensify the information campaign on “no segregation, no collection” policy among residents and consider imposing fines and penalties for violators thereof;
Re-establish the MRFs of the concerned Barangays and require from its officials and constituents, strict compliance to the guidelines and criteria set under RA No. 9003;
Allocate funds for the construction and operation of a sanitary landfill as a final disposal site for solid wastes; and
Hasten the implementation of all SWM related PPAs to enforce proper sorting, segregation, composting, recycling and disposal of waste materials to efficiently address solid wastes concerns within the Municipality.

We recommended that Management:

Ensure that planned PPAs for SEF are optimally implemented/utilized for the efficient and timely delivery of targeted services and benefits to the constituents in accordance with the proper utilization of the fund; 

Use the correct format of the Income and Expenditure Estimates and include the previous years’ unexpended balances as well as the continuing appropriation in determining the net amount available for appropriation;

Require the liquidation of financial assistance granted to DepEd Officials and refrain from granting the same. Instead the Municipality can provide the supplies and materials needs of the agency/different schools in accordance with the guidelines and accounting procedures to effectively monitor and determine whether or not the funds were utilized for its intended purpose; and

Require the Municipal Accountant to ensure that proper accounts are used in the recording of the financial transactions and supporting documents thereof are complete.

We reiterated our recommendation that Management:
Direct Officers and Employees with cash advances to immediately submit their liquidation papers, otherwise, require the immediate withholding of salary of those officers and employees who were unable to comply with the requirement;
Require the Municipal Accountant to closely monitor the liquidation of outstanding cash advances and send written demand on the submission of liquidation report within ten days before the thirty-day period, pursuant to Section 5.l of COA Circular No. 97-002;
Stop the practice of granting additional cash advances to those who have unliquidated cash advances unless the previous ones are fully settled; and
Institute the appropriate legal actions/sanctions against those erring AOs and be reminded that the Auditor may order the suspension of their salaries, as cited in Section 9.2 and 9.3 of COA Circular No. 2012-004;

We recommended that:
Management require the AOs in the MTO to strictly comply with the timely remittance/deposit of their collections as provided in Section 32 Volume I of the Manual of the NGAS for LGUs;
The AOs exercise diligence in the preparation of RCD and recording of transactions in the cashbook to avoid complexity and discrepancies with other records;
The Municipal Treasurer remind the Collecting clerks to stop the practice of partial remittance. Instead, the collections must be remitted with their corresponding RCDs and their details of collection simultaneously in order to facilitate the proper segregation of collections to their respective funds; and
The Municipal Accountant prepare subsidiary ledgers per AO to show the details of collections and remittances as support for the Cash-Local Treasury account.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:

a) Create a General Services Officer (GSO) position that will discharge on a full time basis the property custodianship functions and the receipt, issuance and recording of the procurement and issuance of supplies and property; maintain updated Property Cards per category on all property, plant and equipment as recorded in the list of Property, Plant and Equipment of accounting records; and facilitate the proper conduct of the physical count and preparation of the RPCPPE;

b) Require the Municipal Accountant to maintain property ledger cards consistent with their accounting records;

c) Require both offices to reconcile and work out on tracing any resulting difference, establish its existence/non-existence and determine from there any further action that may be undertaken; and

d) Maintain and renew all Acknowledgment Receipt for Equipment every three years for the signature of the holder of each item listed in the prepared RPCPPE or based on the old Memorandum Receipts on file.

We reiterated our recommendation that management: 
(a) Strictly enforce settlement of all unliquidated cash advances as of December 31, 2015 and every year thereafter; 
(b) Stop granting additional cash advances to officers and employees unless the previous ones are fully settled to avoid accumulation of the same; and (c) Initiate appropriate legal actions against former and current accountable Officer/Employees if warranted.

We recommended that the Municipal Government endeavor to further improve its process in recording and overall management of RPT and SET Receivables through the following strategies:
Require the Municipal Assessor, Municipal Treasurer and Municipal Accountant to strictly follow the proper process in recording of RPT and SET Receivables as prescribed under Section 248 of RA No. 7160 and Section 20, Volume I of  New Government Accounting System for Local Government Units;
Require the Municipal Accountant to credit accounts RPT and SET Receivables upon collection pursuant to Section 24 and 25, Volume II of the Manual on the New Government Accounting System;
Cause the posting of a Notice of Delinquency in the Payment of Real Property Tax at the main entrance of the Municipal Hall and in other publicly accessible place and conspicuous place in each barangay of the municipality in accordance with Section 254 of RA No. 7160; and
Require the Municipal Accountant to maintain a subsidiary ledger pertaining to RPT and SET Receivables.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:
Direct the Municipal Council for the Protection of Children to actively perform their duties and responsibilities to ensure full strengthening and implementation of the LCPC programs, projects and activities;
Widen the scope of the programs, projects and activities for LCPC as enumerated in Section II of DILG Memorandum Circular No. 2012-120 and prioritize the PPAs	with long term effects/involvement on children;
Direct the Municipal Budget Officer to appropriate measures to control the charges made under the appropriations of programs, projects and activities to which is was created; and
Institute strong internal control over municipal transactions to ensure that the municipal government has a balanced budget and that funds allocated for the delivery of basic services and development projects are utilized as intended.
